  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Diffusive shock acceleration (DSA)</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Diffusive shock acceleration</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Mechanism / Concept</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Intermediate</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key Papers:</th><td>Morlino et al.; Bell (2011)</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>DSA is a first-order Fermi process in which particles gain energy by repeatedly crossing a shock and scattering off magnetic turbulence on either side. The statistical energy gain per cycle leads to a power-law spectrum whose index depends on the shock compression ratio.</p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Scattering</strong> — Magnetic turbulence scatters particles, isotropizing their directions locally and allowing repeated shock crossings.</li>
      <li><strong>Energy gain</strong> — Each crossing yields a fractional energy gain proportional to the shock speed in the plasma frame.</li>
      <li><strong>Spectral index</strong> — For strong non-relativistic shocks the canonical index is ~2 (in energy), modified by obliquity and relativistic effects.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>2603.16647 solves a spatially-dependent transport equation for particles accelerated at recollimation shocks using DSA boundary conditions. The paper shows how diffusion regime and shock obliquity alter cutoff shapes and maximum energies; see [[particle-acceleration-oblique-shocks]] and [[recollimation-shocks]].</p>

    <h2>Key references</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Bell 2011 — review on DSA and magnetic field amplification.</li>
      <li>Morlino et al. — transport-method precedents used in 2603.16647.</li>
    </ol>

